{"type":"text","timestamp":1778379348589,"sessionID":"ses_1f05cc1c3ffepPS2Ehzz0PJ43W","part":{"id":"prt_e0fab57660013FvGq8gjEpB7jA","messageID":"msg_e0fab4b3b001E0xOskR6ognZ9t","sessionID":"ses_1f05cc1c3ffepPS2Ehzz0PJ43W","type":"text","text":"The literature supports a p24 hetero-oligomeric membrane complex that cycles between ER and Golgi, acts as a COPII cargo receptor for GPI-anchored proteins, and includes members of p24 alpha/beta/gamma/delta subfamilies. One issue-linked numeric reference to `PMC2265561` was not a PMID and resolved as an unrelated PubMed record, so I will not use it as definition provenance.","time":{"start":1778379347814,"end":1778379348588},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0bb1b63175911fc90169ffea53c4708195a63641717b047a36","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778379363791,"sessionID":"ses_1f05cc1c3ffepPS2Ehzz0PJ43W","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_vEiVfxkmbzzNhcflp0TD7jAI","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: RESEARCH.md\n+# Research: p24 Cargo Receptor Complex\n+\n+## PMID:32456004 \"Dual Independent Roles of the p24 Complex in Selectivity of Secretory Cargo Export from the Endoplasmic Reticulum.\"\n+\n+This paper supports the requested term as a p24 protein complex that acts as a cargo receptor in ER export, particularly for GPI-anchored proteins, and participates at ER exit sites during COPII-dependent secretory cargo export.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32456004 \"The p24 protein complex acts as a specific cargo receptor for GPI-anchored proteins by facilitating their ER exit through a specialized export pathway in yeast.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32456004 \"The p24 complex is a heteromeric protein complex formed by members of the conserved p24 family protein, which are abundant type I transmembrane proteins that cycle between ER and Golgi apparatus thanks to cytosolic COPII and COPI coat-binding signals\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32456004 \"This result suggests that the multireceptor complexes are assembled at the level of ER exit sites during the COPII vesicle formation.\"\n+\n+## PMID:34647572 \"Differential use of p24 family members as cargo receptors for the transport of glycosylphosphatidylinositol-anchored proteins and Wnt1.\"\n+\n+This paper supports p24 complexes as COPII cargo receptors and documents subfamily composition.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:34647572 \"Complexes of p24 proteins act as cargo receptors for the transport of COPII vesicles from the endoplasmic reticulum (ER).\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:34647572 \"Each p24 complex is known to contain members from all four p24 subfamilies (p24α, p24β, p24γ and p24δ).\"\n+\n+## PMID:27569046 \"3D Structure and Interaction of p24β and p24δ Golgi Dynamics Domains: Implication for p24 Complex Formation and Cargo Transport.\"\n+\n+This paper supports that p24 family proteins form hetero-oligomeric complexes needed for ER-to-Golgi cargo transport.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:27569046 \"The p24 family consists of four subfamilies (p24α, p24β, p24γ, and p24δ), and the proteins are thought to form hetero-oligomeric complexes for efficient transport of cargo proteins from the endoplasmic reticulum to the Golgi apparatus.\"\n+\n+## PMID:19566487 \"The p24 family and selective transport processes at the ER-Golgi interface.\"\n+\n+This review supports p24 family proteins as early secretory pathway transmembrane proteins that bind COPI and COPII coats and participate in cargo selection at the ER-Golgi interface.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:19566487 \"Type-I transmembrane proteins of approximately 24 kDa are abundantly present in the membranes of the early secretory pathway, and bind the COPI and COPII coat complexes that cover vesicles travelling between the membranes.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:19566487 \"One model proposes that p24 proteins couple cargo selection in the lumen with vesicle coat recruitment in the cytosol.\"\n+\n+## PMID:26224213 \"p24 family proteins: key players in the regulation of trafficking along the secretory pathway.\"\n+\n+This review supports the broader secretory pathway role of p24 family proteins and their modulation of specific cargos.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26224213 \"p24 family proteins have been known for a long time, but their functions have remained elusive. However, they are emerging as essential regulators of protein trafficking along the secretory pathway, influencing the composition, structure, and function of different organelles in the pathway, especially the ER and the Golgi apparatus.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26224213 \"In addition, they appear to modulate the transport of specific cargos, including GPI-anchored proteins, G-protein-coupled receptors, or K/HDEL ligands.\"\n+\n+## Reference Note\n+\n+The issue comment linked `https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2265561/`; this is a PMCID-style URL, not a PMID. The numeric value `PMID:2265561` resolves to an unrelated Arabian oryx chromosome paper, so it was not used as ontology definition provenance.\n*** Add File: DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+# Design Patterns: p24 Cargo Receptor Complex\n+\n+## Relevant Pattern\n+\n+`src/design_patterns/protein_complex_by_activity.yaml` defines protein complexes by molecular function using:\n+\n+* genus: `GO:0032991 protein-containing complex`\n+* relation: `capable_of` some molecular function\n+* equivalent axiom form: `protein complex and capable_of some <function>`\n+\n+The existing parent term `GO:0062137 cargo receptor complex` already follows a closely related logical definition:\n+\n+* `intersection_of: GO:0032991 ! protein-containing complex`\n+* `intersection_of: capable_of GO:0038024 ! cargo receptor activity`\n+* `intersection_of: part_of GO:0016020 ! membrane`\n+\n+## Existing Ontology Precedent\n+\n+Relevant existing term:\n+\n+* `GO:0062137 cargo receptor complex`: cellular component, defined as a membrane protein-containing complex capable of cargo receptor activity.\n+* `GO:0061852 retrograde cargo receptor complex, Golgi to ER`: asserted as `is_a GO:0062137` and uses `capable_of_part_of` to a transport process, not a new equivalence axiom.\n+\n+## Decision\n+\n+The requested term is a named biological complex, not a fully compositional class where the label, definition, and logical definition can be reduced to the activity alone. The parent `GO:0062137` supplies the logical cargo receptor complex classification. For the p24-specific child, use an asserted `is_a GO:0062137` and a necessary-only `capable_of_part_of GO:0006888` relationship to capture its role in ER-to-Golgi vesicle-mediated transport without over-specifying equivalence conditions.\n+\n+No new `intersection_of` axioms are added.\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA RESEARCH.md\nA DESIGN_PATTERNS.md","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,40 @@\n+# Research: p24 Cargo Receptor Complex\n+\n+## PMID:32456004 \"Dual Independent Roles of the p24 Complex in Selectivity of Secretory Cargo Export from the Endoplasmic Reticulum.\"\n+\n+This paper supports the requested term as a p24 protein complex that acts as a cargo receptor in ER export, particularly for GPI-anchored proteins, and participates at ER exit sites during COPII-dependent secretory cargo export.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32456004 \"The p24 protein complex acts as a specific cargo receptor for GPI-anchored proteins by facilitating their ER exit through a specialized export pathway in yeast.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32456004 \"The p24 complex is a heteromeric protein complex formed by members of the conserved p24 family protein, which are abundant type I transmembrane proteins that cycle between ER and Golgi apparatus thanks to cytosolic COPII and COPI coat-binding signals\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32456004 \"This result suggests that the multireceptor complexes are assembled at the level of ER exit sites during the COPII vesicle formation.\"\n+\n+## PMID:34647572 \"Differential use of p24 family members as cargo receptors for the transport of glycosylphosphatidylinositol-anchored proteins and Wnt1.\"\n+\n+This paper supports p24 complexes as COPII cargo receptors and documents subfamily composition.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:34647572 \"Complexes of p24 proteins act as cargo receptors for the transport of COPII vesicles from the endoplasmic reticulum (ER).\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:34647572 \"Each p24 complex is known to contain members from all four p24 subfamilies (p24α, p24β, p24γ and p24δ).\"\n+\n+## PMID:27569046 \"3D Structure and Interaction of p24β and p24δ Golgi Dynamics Domains: Implication for p24 Complex Formation and Cargo Transport.\"\n+\n+This paper supports that p24 family proteins form hetero-oligomeric complexes needed for ER-to-Golgi cargo transport.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:27569046 \"The p24 family consists of four subfamilies (p24α, p24β, p24γ, and p24δ), and the proteins are thought to form hetero-oligomeric complexes for efficient transport of cargo proteins from the endoplasmic reticulum to the Golgi apparatus.\"\n+\n+## PMID:19566487 \"The p24 family and selective transport processes at the ER-Golgi interface.\"\n+\n+This review supports p24 family proteins as early secretory pathway transmembrane proteins that bind COPI and COPII coats and participate in cargo selection at the ER-Golgi interface.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:19566487 \"Type-I transmembrane proteins of approximately 24 kDa are abundantly present in the membranes of the early secretory pathway, and bind the COPI and COPII coat complexes that cover vesicles travelling between the membranes.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:19566487 \"One model proposes that p24 proteins couple cargo selection in the lumen with vesicle coat recruitment in the cytosol.\"\n+\n+## PMID:26224213 \"p24 family proteins: key players in the regulation of trafficking along the secretory pathway.\"\n+\n+This review supports the broader secretory pathway role of p24 family proteins and their modulation of specific cargos.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26224213 \"p24 family proteins have been known for a long time, but their functions have remained elusive. However, they are emerging as essential regulators of protein trafficking along the secretory pathway, influencing the composition, structure, and function of different organelles in the pathway, especially the ER and the Golgi apparatus.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26224213 \"In addition, they appear to modulate the transport of specific cargos, including GPI-anchored proteins, G-protein-coupled receptors, or K/HDEL ligands.\"\n+\n+## Reference Note\n+\n+The issue comment linked `https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2265561/`; this is a PMCID-style URL, not a PMID. The numeric value `PMID:2265561` resolves to an unrelated Arabian oryx chromosome paper, so it was not used as ontology definition provenance.\n\nIndex: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,28 @@\n+# Design Patterns: p24 Cargo Receptor Complex\n+\n+## Relevant Pattern\n+\n+`src/design_patterns/protein_complex_by_activity.yaml` defines protein complexes by molecular function using:\n+\n+* genus: `GO:0032991 protein-containing complex`\n+* relation: `capable_of` some molecular function\n+* equivalent axiom form: `protein complex and capable_of some <function>`\n+\n+The existing parent term `GO:0062137 cargo receptor complex` already follows a closely related logical definition:\n+\n+* `intersection_of: GO:0032991 ! protein-containing complex`\n+* `intersection_of: capable_of GO:0038024 ! cargo receptor activity`\n+* `intersection_of: part_of GO:0016020 ! membrane`\n+\n+## Existing Ontology Precedent\n+\n+Relevant existing term:\n+\n+* `GO:0062137 cargo receptor complex`: cellular component, defined as a membrane protein-containing complex capable of cargo receptor activity.\n+* `GO:0061852 retrograde cargo receptor complex, Golgi to ER`: asserted as `is_a GO:0062137` and uses `capable_of_part_of` to a transport process, not a new equivalence axiom.\n+\n+## Decision\n+\n+The requested term is a named biological complex, not a fully compositional class where the label, definition, and logical definition can be reduced to the activity alone. The parent `GO:0062137` supplies the logical cargo receptor complex classification. For the p24-specific child, use an asserted `is_a GO:0062137` and a necessary-only `capable_of_part_of GO:0006888` relationship to capture its role in ER-to-Golgi vesicle-mediated transport without over-specifying equivalence conditions.\n+\n+No new `intersection_of` axioms are added.\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md","relativePath":"RESEARCH.md","type":"add","patch":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,40 @@\n+# Research: p24 Cargo Receptor Complex\n+\n+## PMID:32456004 \"Dual Independent Roles of the p24 Complex in Selectivity of Secretory Cargo Export from the Endoplasmic Reticulum.\"\n+\n+This paper supports the requested term as a p24 protein complex that acts as a cargo receptor in ER export, particularly for GPI-anchored proteins, and participates at ER exit sites during COPII-dependent secretory cargo export.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32456004 \"The p24 protein complex acts as a specific cargo receptor for GPI-anchored proteins by facilitating their ER exit through a specialized export pathway in yeast.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32456004 \"The p24 complex is a heteromeric protein complex formed by members of the conserved p24 family protein, which are abundant type I transmembrane proteins that cycle between ER and Golgi apparatus thanks to cytosolic COPII and COPI coat-binding signals\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32456004 \"This result suggests that the multireceptor complexes are assembled at the level of ER exit sites during the COPII vesicle formation.\"\n+\n+## PMID:34647572 \"Differential use of p24 family members as cargo receptors for the transport of glycosylphosphatidylinositol-anchored proteins and Wnt1.\"\n+\n+This paper supports p24 complexes as COPII cargo receptors and documents subfamily composition.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:34647572 \"Complexes of p24 proteins act as cargo receptors for the transport of COPII vesicles from the endoplasmic reticulum (ER).\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:34647572 \"Each p24 complex is known to contain members from all four p24 subfamilies (p24α, p24β, p24γ and p24δ).\"\n+\n+## PMID:27569046 \"3D Structure and Interaction of p24β and p24δ Golgi Dynamics Domains: Implication for p24 Complex Formation and Cargo Transport.\"\n+\n+This paper supports that p24 family proteins form hetero-oligomeric complexes needed for ER-to-Golgi cargo transport.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:27569046 \"The p24 family consists of four subfamilies (p24α, p24β, p24γ, and p24δ), and the proteins are thought to form hetero-oligomeric complexes for efficient transport of cargo proteins from the endoplasmic reticulum to the Golgi apparatus.\"\n+\n+## PMID:19566487 \"The p24 family and selective transport processes at the ER-Golgi interface.\"\n+\n+This review supports p24 family proteins as early secretory pathway transmembrane proteins that bind COPI and COPII coats and participate in cargo selection at the ER-Golgi interface.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:19566487 \"Type-I transmembrane proteins of approximately 24 kDa are abundantly present in the membranes of the early secretory pathway, and bind the COPI and COPII coat complexes that cover vesicles travelling between the membranes.\"\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:19566487 \"One model proposes that p24 proteins couple cargo selection in the lumen with vesicle coat recruitment in the cytosol.\"\n+\n+## PMID:26224213 \"p24 family proteins: key players in the regulation of trafficking along the secretory pathway.\"\n+\n+This review supports the broader secretory pathway role of p24 family proteins and their modulation of specific cargos.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26224213 \"p24 family proteins have been known for a long time, but their functions have remained elusive. However, they are emerging as essential regulators of protein trafficking along the secretory pathway, influencing the composition, structure, and function of different organelles in the pathway, especially the ER and the Golgi apparatus.\